 by one over time although the number of training examples remains fixed. This is in contrast with traditional online learning methods that only deal with sequentially added observations, with little attention being paid to streaming features. The critical challenges for online streaming feature selection include: (1) the continuous growth of feature volumes over time; (2) a very large feature space, possibly of unknown or infinite size; and (3) the unavailability of all features before feature selection starts. In the paper, we present a novel Online Streaming Feature Selection (OSFS) method to select strongly relevant and non-redundant features on the fly. An efficient Fast-OSFS algorithm is proposed to improve feature selection performance. The proposed algorithms are evaluated extensively on high-dimensional datasets and also with a real-world case study on impact crater detection. Experimental results demonstrate that the algorithms achieve better compactness and higher accuracy than existing streaming feature selection algorithms." "http://doi.ieeecomputersociety.org/10.1109/TPAMI.2012.197" (20681 64083 859856) new 13 nil nil ((title nil "PrePrint: Online Feature Selection with Streaming Features") (link nil "http://doi.ieeecomputersociety.org/10.1109/TPAMI.2012.197") (description nil "We propose a new online feature selection framework for applications with streaming features where features are supplied continuously and the knowledge of the full feature space is unknown in advance. We define streaming features as features that flow one by one over time although the number of training examples remains fixed. This is in contrast with traditional online learning methods that only deal with sequentially added observations, with little attention being paid to streaming features. The critical challenges for online streaming feature selection include: (1) the continuous growth of feature volumes over time; (2) a very large feature space, possibly of unknown or infin